.TH CMT_INLINE 3 "LIBCMT" "CMT_INLINE" "Inline Functions"

.SH NAME
CMT_INLINE \- Marks functions to be inlined on supported compilers

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #define INCL__INLINE
.br
.B #include <LIBCMT/LIBCMT.h>

.SH DESCRIPTION
Defines a macro to inline functions across supported compilers. Replaces function calls with the function body at compile time to reduce call overhead.

.TP
.B INLINE
Marks a function as inline.

.SH USAGE
.nf
INLINE void function(void) {
    // code
}
.fi

.SH WARNINGS
.nf
- Avoid combining INLINE with 'static' if unnecessary.
- Do not use 'goto' inside inline functions.
- Do not declare static variables inside inline functions.
- Do not use recursion inside inline functions.
- Avoid variable argument lists (va_list, va_arg, ...).
.fi

.SH EXAMPLE
.nf
INLINE int add(void) {
    return 15 + 42;
}

int main(void) {
    printf("%d", add()); // becomes printf("%d", 15 + 42);
    return 0;
}
.fi

.SH NOTES
- Replaces calls with actual code at call sites.
- Inline functions defined in headers do not require external symbol mapping.
- Clang's [[clang::always_inline]] may be unreliable.
- Use INLINE primarily for performance-critical small functions.

